  "response": "Pizzagate is a debunked conspiracy theory that emerged during the 2016 U.S. presidential election. The conspiracy falsely claimed that high-ranking Democratic Party officials were involved in a child sex trafficking ring operating out of a Washington D.C. pizza restaurant called Comet Ping Pong. \n\nThe theory originated from hacked emails from John Podesta, Hillary Clinton's campaign chairman, which conspiracy theorists misinterpreted as containing coded messages about child abuse. Despite no credible evidence supporting these claims, the conspiracy spread widely on social media.\n\nIn December 2016, the conspiracy led to a dangerous real-world incident when a man named Edgar Maddison Welch fired a rifle inside the Comet Ping Pong restaurant, believing he was investigating the alleged trafficking ring. He was arrested and sentenced to four years in prison.\n\nMultiple investigations, including by law enforcement, found absolutely no truth to the conspiracy theory. It has been thoroughly debunked by fact-checkers and journalists. The conspiracy is now widely recognized as a harmful and baseless fabrication that arose from political misinformation and online rumor-mongering.",
